{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UCvpzETJiom5pfhVEzf1mT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand! The escalation happened because lane 3 failed 10 times due to two persistent test violations:\n\n1. CHK-009: Tests mock the food service, so they don't verify FTS/nameTranslations/ranking behavior\n2. CHK-051: Tests mock service methods, so they don't verify real ownership enforcement\n\nThe forge state was reset to `current_lane: 1`, but the user is asking to implement `--lane 1 --cycle 1`. \n\nWait, this doesn't make sense. Why would we re-implement lane 1? That's already done. Let me re-read the state.yaml again...\n\n\nActually, I'm wondering if the forge resets to lane 1 after escalation as a way to start fresh, but the user's explicit request for lane 1 might mean they want me to re-implement it from scratch. Or maybe the forge is designed to cycle through lanes again when recovering from an escalation failure.\n\nWait, I should stop overthinking this. The user is running `/forge:implement --lane 1 --cycle 1`, and there's a review-lane-1.md file that exists, which means this is a retry scenario. According to the implementation guide, I need to parse the violations in that review file and address them in order of severity before doing any new work.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":48642,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":612,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a66ef498-c4fe-4e6b-9ca3-490a028ecc26","uuid":"7a7e0d67-8f2f-421f-86f1-000000000000"}
