{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CFgPuJxhmBSpGi8rGT1VnR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The problem is `src/server/db/index.ts` line 20:\n```typescript\nexport const db = globalForDb._db ?? createDb();\n```\n\nThis calls `createDb()` at module load time if there's no cached instance. During `pnpm build`, Next.js imports this module to collect page data, which triggers `createDb()`, which throws because DATABASE_URL is not set.\n\nEven though the route has `export const dynamic = \"force-dynamic\"`, Next.js still needs to import the module to process it during build.\n\nThe fix: make the database initialization lazy. Instead of calling `createDb()` at module load time, create a getter that lazily initializes the DB.\n\n\nLooking at the learnings file, the auth module was already fixed with a lazy proxy pattern to handle this exact issue. I need to apply the same approach to the DB module—wrapping the database initialization in a lazy proxy so it only gets created when actually accessed, not at import time.\n\nHowever, I'm realizing that Drizzle's complex object structure might not play well with a proxy approach. The tests mock the entire db module anyway, so they bypass the initialization problem, but the build process imports it directly without mocking. The real solution is to make the DB export lazy—either through a getter function or the proxy pattern—but since we're exporting `db` as a const, I need to find a way to defer the creation.\n\nThe proxy approach could work similarly to how auth handles it, using a handler that checks if the database is initialized before accessing properties. Alternatively, I could stub the DATABASE_URL during the build process or skip DB initialization entirely with an environment flag. The proxy pattern seems cleanest, though I'm concerned about whether Drizzle's type system will cooperate with it.\n\nLooking at how the tests handle this—they mock the entire module to return stub functions—suggests the actual implementation doesn't need to be complex. For the build step, the most straightforward solution that preserves the API is making the database initialization lazy.\n\nImplementing the proxy approach...\n\nWriting the lazy initialization handler... I'm considering whether exporting a getter function instead would be cleaner, though that would mean updating all the callers throughout the codebase. Let me check how the auth module implements this lazy proxy pattern to see if there's a better approach I'm missing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":411,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":81973,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1342,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a66ef498-c4fe-4e6b-9ca3-490a028ecc26","uuid":"35a3c5d4-1de9-4a97-a90f-000000000000"}
